## MCP Tooling Reference

> Fill in based on which MCP servers are actually configured for this
> project (see `opencode.json` or equivalent). Only document servers that
> exist — do not describe hypothetical tooling.

### Browser DevTools MCP (if configured)
- Use for: reproducing a reported bug (see AGENTS.md → Bug Reproduction),
  reading console/network output during manual verification, checking
  layout after a DOM/canvas change.
- Filter noise: browser extensions (wallet extensions, password managers,
  etc.) generate console warnings unrelated to this project — ignore
  anything originating from `moz-extension://` or `chrome-extension://`
  URLs, and anything explicitly matching a known-safe pattern already
  documented in the relevant session prompt's Manual Verification Script.
- `--enable-script` is on in opencode.json because interaction
  verification genuinely needs evaluate_script — this was a deliberate
  call, not a default to second-guess.
- `--headless` is intentional: the agent doesn't need a visible window
  for console/DOM checks, and a headless run is what's actually running
  here — there is no window to see, by design, not a sign anything is
  broken.
- Cap automated interaction verification at 2–3 attempts. If
  dispatching synthetic keyboard/click events to prove a game interaction
  (movement, an "interact" trigger, a modal opening) hasn't produced the
  expected DOM change within a couple of tries, stop — do not escalate to
  lower-level checks like reading raw WebGL pixels via readPixels().
  That doesn't answer the actual question (canvas focus, listener target,
  and event timing are all still unverified) and can run a single turn
  long enough to break the underlying model call entirely (this happened
  in Session 1). Report what was tried and what didn't confirm, and ask
  the human to verify that specific interactive step directly — a real
  keypress in a real window resolves in seconds what synthetic-event
  troubleshooting can spiral on for many turns.
- Never point browser automation at a default/personal browser profile.
  Use an isolated, dedicated testing profile.

### Documentation MCP (if configured, e.g. Context7)
- Consult before implementing anything using a library API not already
  confirmed in this project's stack-pattern docs (e.g. `docs/<stack>-patterns.md`).
  Training data goes stale; a library's current docs do not.
- After confirming a pattern works in this project, add it to the relevant
  stack-pattern doc so future sessions don't need to re-verify it.

### Code Search MCP (grep.app, configured)
- Use for: seeing how other real projects actually use a library API in
  practice — a different job from Context7, which gives the library's own
  official reference. Good for "what does a working PixiJS v8 + Vue
  integration look like elsewhere" style questions, not just "what does
  this method's signature say."
- Free, remote, no auth required.
- Public code only — never a substitute for reading this project's own
  installed skills (.agents/skills/pixijs-migration-v8/) when the two
  disagree; this project's verified constraints win.

